nt of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sabran","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eliyahu, Hersh, Hyman, Mayer, Nadav, Zev.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Hungarian (<b>Sáfrán</b>); Croatian and Slovenian (<b>Šafran</b>); Czech and Slovak (<b>Šafran</b> and <b>Šafrán</b>): from Middle High German <i>saffrān</i>, German <i>Safran</i>, Hungarian <i>sáfrány</i>, Slavic <i>šafran</i> (standard Slovenian is <i>žafran</i>; see below) ‘saffron’, a bright yellow spice and colorant derived from the stigmas of a crocus, hence a metonymic occupational name for a spicer or a nickname for someone with reddish-yellow hair. The word is ultimately derived from Arabic <i>zaʿfarān</i>. The Jewish name is mainly artificial.","Americanized form of Polish   Szafran   and Slovenian <b>Žafran</b>: from Polish <i>szafran</i>, Slovenian <i>žafran</i> ‘saffron’, words of the same ultimately Arabic origin as above."],"variants":[{"name":"Shafran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Simcha, Avi, Meyer, Shoshana, Tsilya, Uri.  Russian Anatoly, Mikhail, Natalya, Oleg, Semyon, Yuriy.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): mainly artificial name, cognate with   Safran  , from eastern Yiddish <i>shafran</i>, Polish <i>szafran</i> ‘saffron’."]},{"name":"Szafranski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Bogdan, Halina, Krzysztof, Miroslaw, Stanislaw, Tadeuz, Wieslaw.","Polish (<b>Szafrański</b>): habitational name for someone from either of two places called Szafranki in Masovian and Podlaskie voivodeships, or Szafranów, in Masovian and Podkarpackie voivodeships, all named with <i>szafran</i> ‘saffron’ (see   Safran   1). Compare   Safranski  ."]},{"name":"Szafran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Karol.","Polish, Rusyn (from Poland), and Jewish (from Poland): from Polish <i>szafran</i> ‘saffron’, a topographic name for someone who lived where the saffron crocus grew, a metonymic occupational name for a spicer, or possibly a nickname for someone with yellow hair. See also   Safran  ."]},{"name":"Saffran","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Safran  ."]},{"name":"Safranek","meanings":["Czech (<b>Šafránek</b>): from a diminutive of Czech <i>šafrán</i> ‘saffron’ (see   Safran  ), applied as nickname for someone with reddish yellow hair."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume de Sabran was born in 1250, in Europe. He married Rose DE SALMAND in 1293. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1250–":"1250–Surnud","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1294–1353":"1294–1353","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1353":"1353","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1329":"1329","Ariano Irpino, Avellino, Campania, Italy":"Ariano Irpino, Avellino, Campania, Itaalia","europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"1250–":"1250–Kuollut","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1294–1353":"1294–1353","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1353":"1353","1250":"125